The preparation was pork, avacado, potato, plus others on the inside, and the outside was covered with a tasty chili verde salsa with a garnish of pickled onions. It was very good, and even though the portion was large, it all disappeared from my plate. I was meeting with friends, and the server took the cue that we were having a long conversation. TLDR: Food was fine, service was mostly fine except for lying to us, which caused us to accept more health risk during this pandemic.  My friends from out of state, that I hadn't seen in a long time, were driving through and chose this restaurant to meet me for breakfast around 9 a.m. on Labor Day 2020 because I insisted on a place with outdoor seating due to the COVID pandemic, since there are documented cases of diners in a restaurant being infected through the air indoors by diners at other tables. The hostesses told the person in front of me and then me that they were closing the outdoor seating then at the manager's direction due to expected rain (the outdoor tables have canvas umbrellas at each table, not a roof). My friends were on a tight schedule and trying to find a place nearby that was open for breakfast and had outdoor seating with a roof to protect from the rain the restaurant staff told me was coming seemed like an impossible task in the amount of time we had for our visit, so we decided to risk it and eat indoors at the restaurant (we were willing to risk rain  ourselves from under the table umbrella but didn't think the servers should have to get wet to serve us). After being on the waitlist and texted that a table was ready (not a long wait, only 10 min instead of their estimated 15 min), I pointed out to the (manager? owner?) person who was seating us that the sky looked pretty clear,  and she then said it wasn't because of weather at all, but because they were short-staffed that she would not allow anyone else to be seated at the outdoor tables (there were still a few customers at the outdoor tables already from before I arrived). If they had mentioned that upfront when I first came in, instead of lying about the weather, we *would* have found another restaurant with outdoor seating because finding one with a roof over the outdoor seating wouldn't be a factor. Aside from that lie (either on her part or the hostesses, I don't know) she was pleasant enough and even stopped at our table later to chat for a minute. Our server was also fine and was not involved in the weather/outdoor tables communication with us, so I had no issue with her. So moral of the story, if you want outdoor seating there (a reasonable request in this pandemic) and they say it is unavailable due to weather warnings, get confirmation from them and/or actual local weather forecasts before deciding to dine there indoors instead of choosing another restaurant with outdoor seating that they are using.

The waitress never came back to check on us. After a bit more time, our food came out, but they seem to have forgotten my dish. So I waited, and waited, and watched my friends eat their meals. I decided to ask for manager to see what was going on. The manager came to our table, apologized, and blamed the service on the fact there was a convention downtown. She then walked away. So I never got my food, and nothing to show for my wasted time. I then had to return to work. I can understand and accept that a restaurant is busy, but that's no excuse for the waitress completely abandoning us, and the manager not really showing empathy for the fact we received our food super late if at all. I hate writing this because their food is usually good, but this was intolerable. Never getting my food wasn't the issue, it was the lack of service on the waitress' end, and the lack of care from the manager that caused me to write this. First Watch, I hope you all do better in the future. If you can't provide, simply let your customers know, people will understand. This is a true city breakfast cafe, with efficient service, quality food, and reasonable prices. Excellent variety of Eggs Benedict, and I opted for the salmon and red onion option. The egg was poached to perfection, and the use of fresh toasted brioche was a delight in this classic breakfast entree.  I ordered a side of sausage links, which were very fresh, and had the texture of homemade sausages, not the typical brown and serve variety seen at many places. The water was served chilled in a large vessel along with an empty glass. The coffee was terrific, and served with a cup and personal carafe, even for just one person dining. All in all an excellent breakfast spot serving up quality food in record time.  Great choice!
